The first virtual operator is going to arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western Europe partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not too long to arrive.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (Czech Telecommunications Office) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fees regulation it will likely reach a paradox situation - for some Czech mobile operator customers the SMS that they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (Czech Telecommunications Office), Pavel Dvořák, said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operators.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with their own network no longer has too much possibilities (for the rest, it would be difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought an outstanding decline in prices to which classic operators should also react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entering the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is place for these types of operators and that they can succeed.
In other words, we don’t need to look for examples too far.
In February this year we inform you about the launch of the virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group, which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
Furthermore, in order to work effectively, many fewer customers are enough than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - offer cheap SMS calls and messages that nevertheless often counteract with the more adjusted service offer.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half cheap in terms of competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good hit the bet for a no-trivial target group.
This operator is directed specifically to the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works on this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether similar concept as Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small for access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Furthermore, from the point of view of the service offering is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost sure that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We’re talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta Financial Group in a telephone conversation for mobile.cz.
Indirectly he assured that current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can so that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step later to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephone services.
And how much earlier, better.
With this possibility, we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward at the meetings,” group spokesman Pavel Kaidl said.
So, perhaps better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive at the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this moment we believe the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date, no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field,” said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2's opinion, added: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
And he adds, “In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find some virtual operators until the end of the year.
At this point, we should already have a specific contract on the table that would be possible to study at such a short horizon."
Vodafone directs your attention rather to the compliance of the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this regarding the distribution of spending and infrastructure.
We consider it as the biggest contribution from the customers’ perspective.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom setting up a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile.”
Responsible offices - with operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, leading to a decline in prices and thus to a decline in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull out of the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure to ČTU was at the time of U:fon entry for T-Mobile society.
This is a testimony of public information accessible on the CTU websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player to the market would suppose to him and, above all, to his services.
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not only about the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (ÚOHS).
However, this expressed its typical position towards this problem.
“The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile market would be possible after a convention was closed on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
No agreement has been closed until today since the offer of the potential interested rather was not interesting enough for classic operators,” added Kristian Chalupa of the U.O.H.S. Foreign Relations Department.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that should represent consumer interests is more than consideration, besides it, no one should take advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa added: “Abroad where virtual operators normally work, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the low prices of mobile phone services.”
Obviously, the pressure regarding the proper functioning of the market media and the price drop does not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
Really the dramatically shocking in this entire case is in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a chance, it is offered by itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in petrol stations because it is clear that it is work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found signs of unfair competition and has therefore no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecom regulators,” Chalupa said.
Interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
Obviously, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by the CTU that telecommunications are from the point of view of the commercial bidding a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a specific segment, it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS should represent a warning that three mobile operators rise flawlessly similarly.
The current complaints of stakeholders (including the GTS Novera society) show that in all negotiations with the operators, there are many similar obstacles.
Loading responsibility in the CTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the UOHS washs hands in this entire matter.
We have met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, recently, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was submitted for the expansion of the competition of ČTU in the field of commercial bidding that was not carried out, even when a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be known perfectly by the representatives of UOHS, but it is obvious that their interests are found elsewhere.
Everything's okay when no one looks
At the same time, something unnoticedly continues to work like a pseudovirtual operator that there are already a few in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services which, however, only a portion are public.
It is usually about companies that are dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few selected people get the price list of these companies.
The magic is where the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that trade conditions in all Czech mobile operators forbid that type of reselling.
"If cases such as those mentioned were discovered, we could talk about infringement under contract conditions that could be translated to the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity performed by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three cited companies, thousands of customers can be reached.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies, they obtain no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike real virtual traders - they noway threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows speculation of this type, however, the services of this company are used only by a desirable so much percent of customers.
They must also agree that your phone’s SIM card is not on your name so they cannot absolutely have it as a normal customer of the operators.”
This is exactly what should look like the minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile phone operators turn their eyes into this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that its business conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, virtually in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators attempted more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened at this time and in no case defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and others began to emerge with him.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it was a burning nail.
By our experience we cannot cease to impress us that the confusion of attributes in these cases suit you.
But let's not despair.
If this information between frames is correct and the virtual operator really arrives in these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market probably begins to move again.
If any of the operators enter virtual mobile phone operators, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolanek on the day of official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem recorded it from the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solo, one to male voice and another to female voice, another with Coro and another instrumental.
The song is commissioned by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chosen for singers alone with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning, I have tried with both and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it was consistent," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
He gained popularity and people made it his own.
The first strophe of the song after the Czechoslovakian emergence in 1918 became naturally part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
