Interview - Blood Returns to Safe
Hema-Québec celebrated his 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec has again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the trust of the public that had been seriously emptied by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and the discontent of the public, the government of Canada made in February 1994 a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, intended to clarify the circumstances that had led to such tragedy and formulate recommendations so that such disaster was no longer reproduced.
While Judge Krever took a long time to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began her activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Decary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After making a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years following, we have recovered the public’s confidence,” he says before proudly claiming that in the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had the subsequent confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " trust is something extremely fragile ".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the principle of precaution.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow’s disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, Decary counts.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélineau’s reports, according to which when we don’t know and when a serious illness can arise from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we introduced exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained more than a month in the UK since the 1980s.
But a few years ago, it has been proven out of doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the principle of precaution that was applied was meaningful.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleid acid testing that allows donors to detect directly in the blood the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We could reduce this period to less than a week.
We thus substantially decrease the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed significantly to lower the risk of AIDS due to blood transfusion.
Today, one per 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-polluted blood.
“This means it will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
Thus, since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, they will spend more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I think today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern,” said Hema-Québec’s head of management.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, for example of the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary follows before emphasizing that in addition to safe supply, Hema-Québec should also provide sufficient supply.
“Needs increase because the population ages.
Since more aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network that groups on average only 3% of Quebeques eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Penuries are very rare.
But members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to don their blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to be regular donor.
Since today’s life is very unfreeful, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood,” Francine Decary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burned.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the placement at the bank of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of them a year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year," precises Dr. Decary who describes this cord blood taking program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they are unable to enjoy this," since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
