Psychology of overlappings: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the Science magazine, people don’t want to lose competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction and while examined by the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active brain zones of the individuals participating in the experiment.
In both games, participants could make money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, by losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the brain cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of the nervous system’s “self prize”.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to cause an intense strate reaction.
To found their theory, the scientific group economists also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against a person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
In addition to that, another group was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 prior to the auction, but in the event of losing the auction, the group members lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure was highlighted.
However, checking the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the group playing “counter failure” were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the “winning group”.
“These results cannot be deducted from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now reach a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York Economics Faculty.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Some 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
The denomination of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms look a lot; they are characteristic of liver infection and ictericy, but their pathogens and caused diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body mood (sperma, vagina mood, saliva).
It is recommended for travelers to protect themselves against A and B virus vaccine, there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a general condition of illness, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that it appears on the skin and in the eyes’ white, the excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Annually a million people die in the world of cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know that he is ill because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and tattooers.
There are currently about 200 million people worldwide suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease is healed if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representatives of the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by the viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
