Intelligent Car Mimics Bee Flight
What would be the best method for developing technologies in order to avoid collision, if not the imitation of the barrier sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bees.
In a surprising project presented at the Japanese CEATEC, the bees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C imitator-type car robotic management system, which gave the characteristics of the bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight, each beer creates its own particular oval space that really resembles a lot to our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role the composite eyes of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser-ray length measuring system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately becomes a manoeuvre to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the bees, modifying the direction by rotating the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
“If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot’s project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a beer makes to avoid other beers.
This process must be carried out in one opening and closing the eyes.
However, unlike the bees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonal, but can only be bidimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities for bees to escape other bees, here they only used as a possibility for the car robot the rotary movement and acceleration additionally the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is greater, meaning they have a longer lifetime than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, not much less the storage capacity.
This apparatus in each second should only process some input signals and react according to the case.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from the above manoeuvres, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No memories of gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step to develop technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan’s calculations, can be incorporated into series-made models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to its destination, avoiding the existing obstacles on its way.
